title: these taste really good
text: These, like the regular Dang chips, are delicious.  They have the same texture (crunchy but not hard), which I love.  They have a little bit of a caramel coloring and just the right amount of caramel flavor -- you can taste it, but it doesn't overtake or conflict with the coconut flavor.  The sea salt is mild but detectable.These have some fiber but they're pretty high in calories and fat.  It's healthful plant fat (i.e., coconut oil), but you would probably want to measure out servings rather than just letting yourself eat.  (I had a snack-sized bag with multiple servings and I ate the whole thing without realizing it...)The pieces are about the size of large coconut shreds.  One great thing was that I got very little breakage, even though my bag had traveled a good, long way with the US Postal Service.  These are gluten free and vegan, if you have dietary restrictions.  Definitely glad I tried these, and I'm sorry they're gone now!

author: JohnAroundTheCornerReviews
title: Exactly THREE ingredients, and you can pronounce all of them EASILY. Coconut, Coconut Sugar, Sea Salt
text: I was amazed to read that this bag of chips only contains THREE ingredients, and two of the ingredients are actually from the same source, assuming that "Coconut Sugar" comes 100% from Coconut.Do look at the picture of the chips in the picture. These chips are as small as you see in the picture, but they are delicious, but if you don't like coconut, don't get these chips.I got the 3.17 ounce bag, which is labeled to contain 3 servings. I can see that as a reasonable serving size, if you can control yourself. Unfortunately, I can see myself as being able to eat three servings at once, so I'm deliberately closing the resealable seal after each two bites, so I have to remind myself that I'm still eating.I saw other reviews that the bag only contains two child-size hands-ful, but I disagree. I'm not going to dump the contents into my hand, but it sure looks like more than two of my hands-fuls, and I have big hands to match my 6'5" height.Do be aware that one serving contains 50% of the recommended daily value of Saturated Fat, so if you are paying attention to those numbers, you might want to avoid this snack, or have very small servings.If you enjoy coconut, and don't mind the high price, then I recommend these chips to you,but if you are counting all the %Daily Value numbers on everything you eat, then you probably want to avoid this snack.You decide.JohnP.S. It is a week later. I have not yet finished the bag. It is delicious, still, but I have to remind myself to drink plenty of fluids when I eat these coconut chips. Otherwise, I feel a lump in my stomach. It's sort of like trying to eat seven saltine crackers in your mouth at one time. You have to have fluid with this product. I've cut my rating from 5 down to 4 stars because of this issue. I love them, but I have to be careful how many I eat at one time.

author: J. Matlock
title: Completely addicting! (in a good way)
text: I stumbled across these looking for something else to have enough items on my Amazon Subscribe and Save order to get the 15% for the month.  I'm not even a coconut fan; usually the flavor is okay but the texture is too much for me.  But I figured I'd give them a try and pawn them off on my daughter (who loves all things coconut), so I added two bags to my order.  A few days after they arrived, I tore open the first bag thinking I'd get it over with...and could not stop eating them.  I finished off that whole family bag...all by myself...in a day. {insert guilt-ridden shame face here}  The 2nd bag didn't even outlast the week...and I made my daughter feel bad for taking a few without asking!  Needless to say, I changed my Subscribe & Save order to more bags, and to every month.In the meantime, while I wait for my June order, I've been all over town looking for them locally.  Sadly, I could only find one place that carried the "plain" in the small bags, and they are priced higher than these family-size bags!!!  I couldn't justify that, so found one other seller on Amazon that had one bag for $4.45 with a $25 order and 'justified' that order by getting a few books I've been wanting.  I'm serious - these are SOOOOOO good!  They don't get all mealy in your mouth like most coconut.  They're perfectly crispy, just a tad sweet, and it's COCONUT, so I don't even feel guilty about the calories (See the book Eat Fat, Lose Fat if that sounds weird).  I'm just trying to figure out how I can stretch my one bag to last the rest of the month until my June order comes.One other thing.  I love the name.  It was kind of fun running all over town, even though I was ultimately disappointed that no one carried them, because I got to tell the Earth Fare manager, the Whole Foods manager, the Target manager, the Wal-Mart manager, and all the local grocery store managers that they really need to order some "DANG!" coconut chips ASAP.  Then they look at me funny and I laugh and explain the name. Fun to say, AMAZING to snack on. Dang! These are good.

name: Dang Gluten Free Toasted Coconut Chips, 4 Flavor Variety Pack, 1.43 Ounce Bags (Pack of 12)
author: JENCARPENTER33
title: DANG, these are amazing!
text: I first tried the Dang line of coconut chips a few weeks ago. I purchased the original flavor first. I loved their sweet and crunchy strips of coconut so much that I decided to venture out and discover their variety pack which included Dang's original recipe, Caramel with Sea Salt, Bacon and Chile Lime. The product shipped within a day of ordering it. I received it packaged in such a delicate manner with bubble wrap,  as to not give the chips an opportunity to break into tiny pieces. I opened one of each bag to sample them. I first tried the one closest to the original flavor which is the Caramel Sea Salt. This flavor was so reminiscent of the original flavor that I hardly noticed a difference other than the occasional taste of a very light salting. They are not salted with chunks of sea salt. They are simply baked with the sea salt in the product. There is no residual salt in the bag that run of the mill sea salt chips or other chip like products may leave. In comparison to the original flavor, the Caramel Sea Salt is perfect to satisfy your sweet and salty needs all at once, while maintaining that signature Dang product crunch! Next I tried the Chile Lime. This flavor packs a punch. I was not expecting the kick it had. I mean my tongue was tingling like I had eaten a medium to hot chili for a second. It was then quickly followed by the tang of the lime. I am not one for hot food items but the combination adding the lime settles it down enough for me to take a few more bites of them. On the heat scale, I would rate this close to a hot nacho cheese or medium salsa. They maintain their coconut crunch through and through. The signature coconut flavor is slightly hidden under all the spice with just a hint of it at the very end. This is not a flavor to get if you are looking to taste the coconut in every bite. This flavor is one for giving you a little kick in the pants! Next, on to the bacon. I really cannot express enough that if you closed your eyes, you would think you  were eating a super crunchy piece of actual bacon! I was kind of taken aback  at how bacon tasting these little guys were. I personally did not care for this particular flavor but my husband and son ate two bags! I would recommend these as a healthier alternative to bacon flavored chips and actual bacon products. They have a light dusting of the bacon flavor but maintain the signature Dang product crunch. There is no hint of coconut at all in this flavor that I could detect. The last flavor is original. I have previously written a review on those and I will say yet again, that these are so crazy addictive that you cannot each just one. I find myself saying I'm only going to have a small handful and that has yet to happen. I never stop there! The original Dang's coconut chip is just genius. It is not overwhelmingly coconut based in any way. As I have said in another review, even if you are not a big fan of coconut flavored foods, give this a try! It is simply a hint of coconut with a sweet milky like flavor and then a crunch. I promise you, Dang's coconut strips will leave you saying "Dang that is a great product!"

title: BEST toasted coconut chips ever!!!!
text: I have long been a fan of toasted coconut, which has a unique buttery, crunchy, sweet, toasty flavor that very few foods have.  However, most toasted coconut brands are inconsistent from batch to batch, varying a LOT in sweetness, saltiness, texture, size of chips (frequently looking more like flakes than chips) and so some bags are better than others.  I don't know HOW they do it or where they source it from, but EVERY bag of Dang I have ever purchased has been "the best" coconut chips.  Perfectly balanced and very consistent and absolutely delicious.  When I buy these in stores, they cost a little more that other brands but they are worth every penny.  I eat these by themselves all of the time, but they also make a great topping for ice cream, and I love mixing these them with toasted almonds in Greek yogurt. You haven't tried toasted coconut chips until you've had these.

title: Coconut has never tasted so good...
text: Of course if you don't like coconut, then you probably won't like this product.  But if you do like coconut, even a little bit, then this will be like a drug.  It is incredible.  When I first bought a small bag before catching a flight at JFK, I was skeptical.  I normally avoid coconut due to its heavy calorie count - despite its proported health benefits - and I often find coconut-based products to be overly sweet, chewy, and/or generally unappealing.  This product, however, is none of those things.  The coconut pieces are thin, light, and crispy.  The coconut flavor is pleasant and natural, and it's only lightly sweetened.  Further, it's also lightly salted, which makes this like the coconut version of kettle corn.  And the calorie count isn't even that bad!  This makes an excellent snack - in fact, I prefer it on its own rather than as a topping to other foods.  My entire family is hooked now - I definitely recommend this product.

author: Yoga Girl
title: Tried two flavors
text: I didn't want to buy a box of 12 (variety or one flavor) so when I saw these at Whole Foods and one sale (2 bars for $4), I thought it was a good opportunity to try them.  I was looking for a bar that is low carb, no sugar/fruit and a few other specifications.1)  Almond Vanilla had an overpowering taste from the pea protein (not good) and not much taste from the vanilla or almonds in my opinion.  The good news is the texture seemed just right (not too dry, not too moist), but alas the flavor issue will keep me from purchasing this again.2)  Chocolate Sea Salt - first off it's very dry (I wish they had better texture like the almond vanilla that I tried first) and it's super salty (and I like salt).  The salt overpowers the chocolate flavor (really didn't taste much like chocolate to me) likely due to the pea protein hampering the chocolate taste and the salt trying to cover the pea protein taste up as well.  I still have half the bar and may try heating it up to see if it tastes better, but likely will not purchase again.I didn't try the lemon flavor (if the sale price was 3 for $6 I would have), but I'm pretty fussy with my lemon flavors and if it doesn't taste natural I likely wouldn't like it and I'm guessing the pea protein would be overwhelming with this bar too even with the green tea.  I will say that the cashier raved about the other products from Dang (which I think contain sugar so I'll have to skip these too).My journey continues for a good low carb no sugar snack (with no dairy or egg) ...

text: I started Keto 5 months ago and have really been struggling to find ready-made Keto food or snacks. I was surprised how much I liked these! The textures are interesting - there's coconut, seeds, some crispy things in a creamy base, making it perfect for savoring each small bite. I carry them in my bag and probably only eat 1/3 a bar at a time, when I need a bite of something a little sweet. Even the faint sweetness of these bars is satisfying since Keto folks are used to no sugar at all. The Lemon Matcha was my favorite. Also, much appreciation to Dang for making something Keto-friendly when the rest of the snack and bar aisles are filled with sugar or starch.

title: Try before you buy!
text: These are awful! We love the coconut chips by Dang and were excited to add these bars to our low carb/Keto lifestyle. We have had plenty of different low carb bars including No Cow (our favorite), Kirkland brand (Costco), Quest, Premiere, and plenty of homemade stuff using almond flour, coconut flour & sugar substitutes so it is not a matter of new flavors or expectations that these would taste like a candy bar! author: John
title: not quite perfect but pretty "dang" good
text: These comments are combined from a friend receiving a gift box and from me. My friend, who follows a keto diet strictly, gave an enthusiastic endorsement for all three flavors in the variety box. My comments would be more reserved, at four stars, because of the texture of these bars. My favorite flavor was chocolate, which surprised me, because I do not like the typical chocolate flavor in specialized dietary products. My least favorite was vanilla almond, until I got used to it. The textures are peculiar, with a bit of crunchy grittiness, but far better than the worst that diet bars can be. I appreciated that all three flavors had a mild natural sweetness that was balanced, not cloying. I keep several dang bars in my office for a quick "emergency ration." They are more palatable than any of the protein bars that I have tried. If you are following a keto diet anyway, you probably will love these bars; if you are not, you might enjoy them, too, if the textures are not too distracting.

author: MariaSmiles
title: Delicious! Small bags, NOT resealable.
text: Unfortunately, these are delicious and healthy, as they are somewhat pricey and I don't like that there's such a small amount in each bag. Yes, this helps provide a bit of discipline, so you are more likely to just eat one serving (or, even more likely to eat the 1.4 servings it's packaged as); however, it is kind of wasteful and I wish there was a more eco-friendly way to package and distribute these, as they are one of my favorite snack foods. I'd purchased the larger bags in the past, with the resealable top, but when I ordered this one, I didn't realize these were the smaller version (sans the resealable feature).In addition to my preference for the taste, I also prefer the ingredients in this** flavor over the plain flavor (coconut sugar** vs sugar, and sea salt** vs salt). Interestingly, despite this flavor being "caramel sea salt", this flavor does not list caramel as an ingredient. Magical.I checked the prices on the subscribe and save for the single pack of the larger size vs the 12-pack of the smaller size, and, as of right now, with a 15% S&S discount on both, and a 10% coupon for the 12-pack, it's only a 1-cent per ounce difference. I'll stick with the larger, resealable bags for now.These are really delicious and quite healthy as a small snack. If you have trouble with willpower, you might have to be creative to help curb your cravings for handfuls of these tasty chips. Oh, and to describe them: they are larger shaved slices of coconut, just the right blend of crispyness and tenderness. If you like coconut at all, you'll probably really love these. I eat them straight, but you could use them as a garnish on a fancy dessert or a tasty topping for a fruit bowl or even ice cream. While I do wish the packaging was different, I hope they keep the edible part exactly as it is.And, heed my warning, these, and the dark chocolate dipped ones are quite possibly addictive. Like, really.I rely on reviews to help me make informed buying decisions. I hope you found this review helpful :)

text: This is the BEST dried coconut I have had, with a great flavor(& sweet) and  very crisp as well.My husband came home with it from the health food store and our family of four could hardly stop eating it!We ate half of the "family" size bag and saved the rest for our dessert that night!We typically don't eat coconut for dessert but this is so sweet, crisp, and full of flavor that you will have a hard time putting it down.This is the smaller bag--they have a 3.17 oz bag that I would recommend unless you are single.YUM.I think this is the biggest bag they make.  It is not tons but well worth the price.  We paid about four bucks for it at our store and the smaller bag is two.  I recommend the larger size since the small one is like a snack for one person.This flavor along with the plain is---Delicious!!!It has a little vanilla/caramel flavor with a hint of Sea Salt and taste like candy!Note, that these are like thin slices of coconut, not tiny shreds.  I am looking forward to trying this in a toffee brittle with almonds or cashews and on my morning oats.Tasty!

text: I bought these bars because I wanted something to replace my protein bars that were full of carbs and sugar.  These definitely do the trick and they're yummy.  The bars are small inside the packaging.  In fact, they could probably use half the packaging, but maybe there isn't enough room for the ingredients list and nutrition info.I've had the chocolate sea salt and just bought the almond vanilla.  I enjoy the flavor; it's not strong or overwhelming.  The bars aren't soft and gooey, they're solid, but easy to bite into and chew.  If crushed, they will break into pieces, which isn't a bad thing.  They're a good size for an afternoon snack or before/after a workout.They're keto friendly too and make for a great snack that's compliant.

Try topping a protein/regular brownie with these, fresh berries, and vanilla Greek yogurt and you have a delicious healthier treat (the coconut chips add an essential textural component which takes the deliciousness to the next level). Just make sure that if you're eating it with fruit (berries or sliced), you eat it ASAP so the chips won't loose their crunch. title: Addictive and Severely YUMMY!  Don't delay, stock up today!
text: OMG, these are so ridiculously delicious I can hardly stand it. They are thin pieces of coconut (not much thicker than, say, a couple pieces of cardstock, and smaller than a pinky finger in area) and out of the bag they look and feel like little pieces of plastic.  But put one in your mouth and wow!  The crunch is like that of a freeze dried item, not a baked or regularly dehydrated coconut chip or chunk.  They are dreadfully addictive but if you just take a small handful the bag can last a few days.  You could also easily eat the entire bag in one sitting, as it's not a huge amount, maybe about a cup or cup and a half with all the little pieces.  Probably great on salad and in yogurt, but I didn't want to adulterate them with other food.My only wish is that they made an unsweetened or even less sweet version, as they are pretty sweet and I don't think coconut really needs that much sweetening to be yummy, especially with the texture these have.  No artificial sweeteners, though!  I'm kinda glad these aren't sold near me because they'd be the only thing I ever ate.  Yum yum yum.

title: Tiny and tasty
text: I've tried another brand of coconut chips before, but couldn't find them again the next time I visited the store where I got them. So, I sadly accepted the idea of never eating tasty coconut chips again. Yesterday I found these at a local store that I frequent, which has an ever changing stock of interesting food and drink items. The packaging and name caught my eye immediately and I bought them. We had some more shopping to do and I kind of forgot about my sweet, sweet coconut chips until this morning when I saw them on the counter. I decided to open themFirst of all they smell heavenly. Think of the most wonderful toasted coconut smell accented with a bit of extra sweetness and you have a good idea. They're also very small, which you can see from the picture on the front of the (beautifully designed) package. "Coconut chips" makes me think of a size like potato chips or banana chips and these are more like coconut strips. This also makes them a little hard to snack on right out of the bag because they're kind of skinny and if you grab a bunch you then need to put that bunch into your mouth without dropping any of the nutty goodness on the floor or something. You'll occasionally get a nice cluster of chips stuck together. For maximum snackability I recommend pouring some into your palm and eating them out of there because the size of the bag may be an issue for people with larger hands. You could also just pour them straight into your mouth. That's also a good idea.I bought some vanilla almond milk on my shopping trip post coconut chip purchase, and while I was snacking I immediately regretted making my coconut chocolate museli the other day because that would have been awesome with the almond milk and some of these tasty little coconut chips on top. They are a great size for topping stuff.My one gripe is that the bag isn't resealable but if you have some masking tape handy that's really just a minor inconvenience. I've never had coconut chips sitting around in an open package for more than a day because they're just that good, so I have no idea if they get stale or something but resealable bags would be a nice improvement.I should mention that I paid 80 cents for one snack size packet of chips. I can't find the exact price of one single bag in a normal retail setting but another reviewer said that they are above a dollar. I'd gladly pay full price for one of these but I was lucky enough to find them at my local store for cheaper.

author: Sneaky Burrito
title: love these!
text: These are delicious and I love the texture. I definitely taste the coconut in them, and they're sweet, as well. They're crisper than most forms of flaked coconut I've purchased in the past, and they work better as a snack (as opposed to a baking ingredient or oatmeal add-in).They do have added sugar, which I'm not thrilled with, but I guess that's what gives them the sweet taste (and it's sweet in a good way, not overpowering). Being coconut, they're high in fat, especially saturated fat. If you eat a whole 1.43 ounce package, you get 70% of your saturated fat for the day. (Technically, this is equivalent to two servings, though.) It's definitely easy to eat the whole package, so watch out for that if you're counting calories.These are vegan, non-GMO, and gluten free. There's no allergen information listed on the package, though.Anyway, like I said, these taste pretty good. Since they're just coconut with a little sugar and salt, it would be hard to change them in any way to reduce the fat content! If you're looking for minimally-processed, natural snacks, and are generally healthy and/or can limit yourself to one serving, you might really like these. I'm afraid to buy more because I think I'll eat them all, though!

title: Great coconut flavor.
text: These are crispy and crunchy, without being too hard, slightly sweet, have very buttery toasted coconut flavor, and shipped quite well from prime pantry. Some of the pieces are nearly 2 inches long. Some are smaller, but there isn't really crumbly dust in the bottom.  They do have cane sugar and salt added. However they are neither overpoweringly sweet or salty. In addition to that, they do have quite a bit of saturated fats, but that is natural for a coconut product. There is no added oil or anything. Ingredients are simple. Coconut, cane sugar, salt. They're also non-gmo project verified. All in all, for me, they're a very tasty little treat. They have a very good coconut flavor. You can eat them alone, put them in homemade trail mix or granola, or my favorite, add them to bananas and milk for breakfast. They have a really good form for just about any use.

title: Vegan, Gluten Free, and Dairy Free.
text: Coming from a family full of people with food sensitivities and allergies, it can be hard to find snacks and treats that are friendly for everyone as well as fairly healthy. The 'dang" toasted coconut chips have not only met, but, exceeded my expectations. They are Gluten Free, Vegan, no cholesterol, Dairy Free and Non GMO. They are literally safe for my entire family.they come in strips that are similar in shape and size to tortilla strips. They have a sweet and buttery coconut flavor that is to die for. Also, they have a lot of crunch. These would be great to mix into salads, to top ice cream and yogurt, or, just plain. You could also make a killer trail mix using these. You get 1.4 servings per 1.43 oz bag. That may not sund like much, but, it is actually quite a bit per serving. There is no trans fat and only 165 calories per serving. These are best fresh from an unopened package, but, if they should lose their crunch, you just pop them in the fridge and they will regain their crunch. Incredible snack. I am hooked.

author: Samuel
title: I've decided I can live without them, but others may have a different  risk-reward ratio.
text: I had room in my Prime Pantry box for one addtional small item.  I remembered that these Coconut Chips tasted surprisingly good--not that they're irresistible, especially to someone who's never cared much for "fresh and raw" coconut meat (or juice)--but slicing them thin and toasting them overcame any previous aversion to coconut.But this time I checked the ingredients.  Let's be honest.  Most consumers will more than likely see this small, 1.4 oz bag as a single serving.  A single oz. of this product contains a full 10 grams of fat--not "good" fat but saturated fat which, according to a best-selling book like Caldwell Esselstyn's "Prevent Heart Disease," is the primary culprit in this national epidemic.  The most effective way of preventing heart disease (along with the course of statin drugs and even surgery) is, according to Dr. Esselstyn, to eliminate saturated fat altogether.If you're a male over 60 with any history of heart disease in your family, you should know that the pictured bag contains 70% of the official "minimal daily requirement" of saturated fat.  I usually balk at anything over 5%.  Your tolerance may be far greater than mine and the reward may outweigh the risk.  On the other hand, if you've already had an omelet for breakfast followed by a Big Mac for lunch and a pizza for dinner, these chips will look  and taste just as good at a later date.

author: Winter Solstice
title: Delicious!
text: Delicious! So buttery & brittle.That's why I like vegan butter made with coconut oil, it has a natural sweet buttery flavor. But these were REALLY buttery good. I'd like that flavor on some freshly popped popcorn, or blueberry muffins while still hot *mmmm*  I wasn't expecting these coconut chips to taste THAT good. Both flavors were delicious but the sea salt and caramel are my favorite. The texture is like soft toffee, it's crunchy but crumbles soon after you start chewing. I expected them to be a little tougher to chew  but they were so buttery & crumbly.I collect raw & vegan snacks, some taste like cardboard with seasoning salt or sugar on'em. So I know to just buy ONE of any new foods, just in case it tastes terrible. Well I will be purchasing more of these coconut chips next time I order.

title: If you think you hate coconuts, you're likely to love these.
text: Lets get something out there right at the beginning. I hate coconuts. I don't like their taste, their texture or the way they seem to judge me when they look at me.So, 'Why?' you may ask would such a person buy a treat based on a thing that he so despises? Because I was bored and I had extra amazon bucks laying around - stop judging me.Ok, seriously, I recall reading about them and one of the commenters mentioned that they really did not taste much at all like coconuts. I figured it was worth a try and I ordered a couple of bags to try out. If I hated them, I have at least two children who will eat anything so I knew it would not go to waste.They arrived and I stashed them away for when I was feeling more culinarily brave and forgot about them for a bit. Ultimately I gave in when all I had left in the house was canned tuna that was 9 months past its eat by date.To put it mildly, I was stunned. This stuff was awesome! Despite the fact that it is absolutely tasty and delicious, it also left me satisfied kind of quickly. I have no way to really explain this. Given how much I liked them, I would have figured I would plow through them and finish them off in one go. But that did not happen.And they go great with tuna.UPDATE: So I have gone through these finally. It's odd. They are good, there is no doubt about that. But they are not the kind of thing where you sit down and finish off a whole bag in one sitting. I just have a little bit now and then and I just feel satisfied. As good as these things taste, you would think that scarfing them down would be normal. So for me, its looks like I go through two bags a month.

title: Simple Ingredients...ADDICTIVE!
text: I received a sample of these in my monthly Birchbox. I don't know if it was a good or bad thing because once I tried these coconut chips I was HOOKED, and ordered a bunch off of Amazon!I honestly am not a big coconut fan, it's a texture thing, but these are a perfect snack. I don't mind the coconut flavor with these. There's not a lot of ingredients, I think it's just coconut, sugar & salt. You know what you are eating. They have a nice crunch. It's addictive.A complaint is that 1 (small) serving is 100+calories, and these bags have 2 servings each. Some may want to eat the entire bag...I guess it's not too bad though, but if you get addicted like we have, the bags start to add up:)A more serious complaint though is that we noticed a few of the bags that came in this bulk order tasted very "off". It's hard to describe, but it wasn't good. So bad we had to toss them. Overall, we love them, and think they are a great healthy snack to have when you are craving something sweet& crunchy!

I have also tried the regular flavor and like it just as much.  They are pretty similar.  I need to try the chocolate and yogurt-dipped ones now.

title: "Dang", these chips are so yummy!
text: I first tried these chips while I was vacationing in California.  I loved them so much that I had to find out where I could buy.  As usual,I was able to find it at Amazon.  I was reluctant about how these would taste as I am not a fan of coconut, per se.  I have to say, these were so yummy.  Highly recommended!
